{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612396"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:22:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:22:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16275"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16275"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.87,0,0.05,0.03,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8966"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74790"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8966"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16275"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60276"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2299"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"10676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21336"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21340"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74790"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise healthy 7-year-old girl presents with breast development and pubic hair growth. Blood tests show elevated luteinising hormone and follicle stimulating hormone levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the underlying mechanism of central precocious puberty?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Early activation of hypothalamic gonadotropin release","Independent ovarian hormone production","Increased adrenal androgen production","Abnormal peripheral gonadotropin release","Primary dysfunction of gonadal tissue"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECentral precocious puberty results from \u003Cstrong\u003Eearly activation of hypothalamic gonadotropin release\u003C/strong\u003E. This leads to increased gonadotropin release, which stimulates sex hormone production and subsequent development of secondary sexual characteristics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndependent ovarian hormone production\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes peripheral precocious puberty, as seen with hormone-secreting tumours\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased adrenal androgen production\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs in congenital adrenal hyperplasia, causing peripheral precocious puberty\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbnormal peripheral gonadotropin release\u003C/strong\u003E - This is rare and would be gonadotropin-independent\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary dysfunction of gonadal tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - This would typically cause delayed rather than precocious puberty\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe elevated gonadotropins (LH and FSH) confirm this is a central process, as these would be suppressed in peripheral precocious puberty.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Central precocious puberty occurs due to early activation of the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis, leading to increased gonadotropin release.","Secondary sexual characteristics appearing before age 8 in girls or age 9 in boys is considered precocious puberty.","Central precocious puberty follows the normal sequence of pubertal development but occurs at an inappropriately early age."],"references":["Kilberg MJ, Vogiatzi MG. Approach to the Patient: Central Precocious Puberty. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2023 Jul 14;108(8):2115-2123. doi: 10.1210/clinem/dgad081. PMID: 36916130.","Alghamdi A. Precocious Puberty: Types, Pathogenesis and Updated Management. Cureus. 2023 Oct 22;15(10):e47485. doi: 10.7759/cureus.47485. PMID: 38021712; PMCID: PMC10663169.","Chen M, Eugster EA. Central Precocious Puberty: Update on Diagnosis and Treatment. Paediatr Drugs. 2015 Aug;17(4):273-81. doi: 10.1007/s40272-015-0130-8. PMID: 25911294; PMCID: PMC5870137.","Lissauer, T., \u0026 Carroll, W. (Eds.). (2021). Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book: Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60276"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16275"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60276"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T06:58:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T06:59:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8966"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74790"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"